hasNext.haxe_doc: Returns true if the iterator has other items, false otherwise.

next.haxe_doc: Moves to the next item of the iterator.

new.haxe_doc: Iterate from [min] (inclusive) to [max] (exclusive). If [max <= min], the iterator will not act as a countdown.

class.haxe_doc: Integer iterator. Used for interval implementation.

length.haxe_doc: The number of characters in the String.

toUpperCase.haxe_doc: Returns an String where all characters have been uppercased.

toLowerCase.haxe_doc: Returns an String where all characters have been lowercased.

charAt.haxe_doc: Returns the character at the given position. Returns the empty String if outside of String bounds.

charCodeAt.haxe_doc: Returns the character code at the given position. Returns [null] if outside of String bounds.

indexOf.haxe_doc: Returns the index of first occurence of [value] Returns [1-1] if [value] is not found. The optional [startIndex] parameter allows you to specify at which character to start searching. The position returned is still relative to the beginning of the string.

lastIndexOf.haxe_doc: Similar to [indexOf] but returns the latest index.

split.haxe_doc: Split the string using the specified delimiter.

substr.haxe_doc: Returns a part of the String, taking [len] characters starting from [pos]. If [len] is not specified, it takes all the remaining characters.

new.haxe_doc: Creates a copy from a given String.

class.haxe_doc: The basic String class.

concat.haxe_doc: Returns a new Array by appending [a] to [this].

join.haxe_doc: Returns a representation of an array with [sep] for separating each element.

pop.haxe_doc: Removes the last element of the array and returns it.

push.haxe_doc: Adds the element [x] at the end of the array.

reverse.haxe_doc: Reverse the order of elements of the Array.

shift.haxe_doc: Removes the first element and returns it.

slice.haxe_doc: Copies the range of the array starting at [pos] up to, but not including, [end]. Both [pos] and [end] can be negative to count from the end: -1 is the last item in the array.

sort.haxe_doc: Sort the Array according to the comparison function [f]. [f(x,y)] should return [0] if [x == y], [>0] if [x > y] and [<0] if [x < y].

splice.haxe_doc: Removes [len] elements starting from [pos] an returns them.

toString.haxe_doc: Returns a displayable representation of the Array content.

unshift.haxe_doc: Adds the element [x] at the start of the array.

insert.haxe_doc: Inserts the element [x] at the position [pos]. All elements after [pos] are moved one index ahead.

remove.haxe_doc: Removes the first occurence of [x]. Returns false if [x] was not present. Elements are compared by using standard equality.

copy.haxe_doc: Returns a copy of the Array. The values are not copied, only the Array structure.

iterator.haxe_doc: Returns an iterator of the Array values.

class.haxe_doc: An Array is a storage for values. You can access it using indexes or with its API. On the server side, it's often better to use a [List] which is less memory and CPU consuming, unless you really need indexed access.

apply.haxe_doc: * Copies properties from one object to another. Conflicting tweens are stopped automatically * @example Actuate.apply (MyClip, { alpha: 1 } ); * @param target The object to copy to * @param properties The object to copy from * @param customActuator A custom actuator to use instead of the default (Optional) * @return The current actuator instance, which can be used to apply properties like onComplete or onUpdate handlers

effects.haxe_doc: * Creates a new effects tween * @param target The object to tween * @param duration The length of the tween in seconds * @param overwrite Sets whether previous tweens for the same target and properties will be overwritten (Default is true) * @return An EffectsOptions instance, which is used to select the kind of effect you would like to apply to the target

pause.haxe_doc: * Pauses tweens for the specified target objects * @param ... targets The target objects which will have their tweens paused. Passing no value pauses tweens for all objects

reset.haxe_doc: * Resets Actuate by stopping and removing tweens for all objects

resume.haxe_doc: * Resumes paused tweens for the specified target objects * @param ... targets The target objects which will have their tweens resumed. Passing no value resumes tweens for all objects

stop.haxe_doc: * Stops all tweens for an individual object * @param target The target object which will have its tweens stopped * @param properties A string, array or object which contains the properties you wish to stop, like "alpha", [ "x", "y" ] or { alpha: null }. Passing no value removes all tweens for the object (Optional) * @param complete If tweens should apply their final target values before stopping. Default is false (Optional) * @param sendEvent If a complete() event should be dispatched for the specified target. Default is true (Optional)

timer.haxe_doc: * Creates a tween-based timer, which is useful for synchronizing function calls with other animations * @example Actuate.timer (1).onComplete (trace, "Timer is now complete"); * @param duration The length of the timer in seconds * @param customActuator A custom actuator to use instead of the default (Optional) * @return The current actuator instance, which can be used to apply properties like onComplete or to gain a reference to the target timer object

transform.haxe_doc: * Creates a new transform tween * @example Actuate.transform (MyClip, 1).color (0xFF0000); * @param target The object to tween * @param duration The length of the tween in seconds * @param overwrite Sets whether previous tweens for the same target and properties will be overwritten (Default is true) * @return A TransformOptions instance, which is used to select the kind of transform you would like to apply to the target

tween.haxe_doc: * Creates a new tween * @example Actuate.tween (MyClip, 1, { alpha: 1 } ).onComplete (trace, "MyClip is now visible"); * @param target The object to tween * @param duration The length of the tween in seconds * @param properties The end values to tween the target to * @param overwrite Sets whether previous tweens for the same target and properties will be overwritten (Default is true) * @param customActuator A custom actuator to use instead of the default (Optional) * @return The current actuator instance, which can be used to apply properties like ease, delay, onComplete or onUpdate

update.haxe_doc: * Creates a new tween that updates a method rather than setting the properties of an object * @example Actuate.update (trace, 1, ["Value: ", 0], ["", 1]).onComplete (trace, "Finished tracing values between 0 and 1"); * @param target The method to update * @param duration The length of the tween in seconds * @param start The starting parameters of the method call. You may use both numeric and non-numeric values * @param end The ending parameters of the method call. You may use both numeric and non-numeric values, but the signature should match the start parameters * @param overwrite Sets whether previous tweens for the same target and properties will be overwritten (Default is true) * @return The current actuator instance, which can be used to apply properties like ease, delay, onComplete or onUpdate

filter.haxe_doc: * Creates a new BitmapFilter tween * @param reference A reference to the target's filter, which can be an array index or the class of the filter * @param properties The end properties to use for the tween * @return The current actuator instance, which can be used to apply properties like ease, delay, onComplete or onUpdate

color.haxe_doc: * Creates a new ColorTransform tween * @param color The color value * @param strength The percentage amount of tint to apply (Default is 1) * @param alpha The end alpha of the target. If you wish to tween alpha and tint simultaneously, you must do them both as part of the ColorTransform. A value of null will make no change to the alpha of the object (Default is null) * @return The current actuator instance, which can be used to apply properties like ease, delay, onComplete or onUpdate

sound.haxe_doc: * Creates a new SoundTransform tween * @param volume The end volume for the target, or null if you would like to ignore this property (Default is null) * @param pan The end pan for the target, or null if you would like to ignore this property (Default is null) * @return The current actuator instance, which can be used to apply properties like ease, delay, onComplete or onUpdate

hasField.haxe_doc: Tells if an object has a field set. This doesn't take into account the object prototype (class methods).

field.haxe_doc: Returns the field of an object, or null if [o] is not an object or doesn't have this field.

callMethod.haxe_doc: Call a method with the given object and arguments.

fields.haxe_doc: Returns the list of fields of an object, excluding its prototype (class methods).

isFunction.haxe_doc: Tells if a value is a function or not.

compare.haxe_doc: Generic comparison function, does not work for methods, see [compareMethods]

compareMethods.haxe_doc: Compare two methods closures. Returns true if it's the same method of the same instance.

isObject.haxe_doc: Tells if a value is an object or not.

copy.haxe_doc: Make a copy of the fields of an object.

makeVarArgs.haxe_doc: Transform a function taking an array of arguments into a function that can be called with any number of arguments.

parseInt.haxe_doc: Convert a String to an Int, parsing different possible representations. Returns [null] if could not be parsed.

parseFloat.haxe_doc: Convert a String to a Float, parsing different possible reprensations.

random.haxe_doc: Return a random integer between 0 included and x excluded.

class.haxe_doc: The standard Float type, this is a double-precision IEEE 64bit float.
The standard Int type. Its precision depends on the platform.

typedef.haxe_doc: The unsigned Int type is only defined for Flash9. It's currently handled the same as a normal Int.

enum.haxe_doc: The standard Boolean type is represented as an enum with two choices.

class.haxe_doc: Dynamic is an internal compiler type which has special behavior. See the haXe language reference for more informations.

An Iterable is a data structure which has an iterator() method. See [Lambda] for generic functions on iterable structures.
